<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
Kavlax the Many Headed, when possessed, has only head equipment slot, which *is* misleading, because both his name and description imply manyheadedness, so one would expect at least 2 heads (adding additional head wouldn't disrupt anything much, he has wimpy hp which could be balancing factor for having the best equipment-wise body). <p>
<a href="./MassimilianoMarangio">MassimilianoMarangio</a>: This was also posted on the old <a class="external" href=".forum.t-o-m-e.net/viewtopic.php?t=3516"><img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/moin-www.png" alt="[WWW]" height="11" width="11">bug forum</a>, without an answer... 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./StarweaverBlue">StarweaverBlue</a></strong>: If possesion is a mental thing, maybe you're only getting one of the heads under your control and the others are laying around limp? (Would also explain his general suckyness that I've herad about.) Anyone have any thoughts on how the mind of a multi-headed (and multi-brained?) creature works? <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile.png" alt=":)" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./SimonSorc">SimonSorc</a>: according to the disney-type legends, heads have distinct personalities and argue all the time. But you wouldn't get that in a serious theme; in Dungeons&amp;Dragons Tiamat has 5 heads and the only argument is how the player will survive different 5 breaths at once? (-; 
</p>
<p>
Seriously. Give Kavlax some heads according to theme(someone read Tolkien and count heads), and boost his stats a bit so he doesn't feel weak for his level (I'd be against lowering his level - unless theme makes him a baby or weakling). 
</p>
<p>
He's definitively not overpowered for possessors even with 3 or 4 heads... 
</p>
<p>
Possessors are used to controlling greater Kraken's 3 heads, this shouldn't be different. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./FuriousOne">FuriousOne</a>: Just a comment - Kavlax is <strong>not</strong> a Tolkienian monster. Reading Tolkien won't help you much. AFAIK, no dragon had more than one head on Arda. The only dragons to whom Tolkien referred by name (in canon) were Ancalagon, Smaug, and Glaurung.  
</p>

    <ul>

 <strong><a href="./ZasVid">ZasVid</a></strong>: And Scatha the Worm. 
    </ul>


<p>
<a href="./MassimilianoMarangio">MassimilianoMarangio</a>: Itangast is listed in the MECCG, as well as some other dragons not in ToME.  
</p>

    <ul>

 <strong><a href="./FuriousOne">FuriousOne</a></strong>: AFAIK Scatha and Ithangast were mentioned in the HoME works by Christopher Tolkien, not by JRR himself, but I might be wrong. I was referring to what's considered canonical (Hobbit, Silmarillion, LoTR - though Scatha might have been in the Silmarillion).  [/split hair] <p>
 <strong><a href="./ZasVid">ZasVid</a></strong>: Scatha was mentioned in Appendices to LotR, in the one about rulers of Rohan (or about dwarves). 
</p>

    </ul>


<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: I've always wondered how the critter in the movie <em>Willlow</em> would stack up to a 2-headed hydra or any of the Tolkienien dragons. I mean, obviously it wasn't too smart, but still...  
</p>

    <ul>

 Rool: Rats! Big rats!  Franjean: What? What? Oh, Rool, you and your stupid rat dreams. 
    </ul>


<p>
(I couldn't find a good quote relevant to that little scene... ah well.) 
</p>

    <ul>

 <a href="./SimonSorc">SimonSorc</a>: I guess he's the dragon equivalent of Frodo; mostly something to be ashamed of. <p>
 <strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Since when was Frodo someone to be ashamed of? <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/tongue.png" alt=":-?" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
 Frodo couldn't survive the barrows-down on his own, even if we give him that longsword we're all thinking of. And he's no mage either. I'm suspecting yeek ancestry, while Kavlax must had a level 1 sickly yeek as a rolemodel to imitate. (-; 
</p>
<p>
 <strong><a href="./FuriousOne">FuriousOne</a></strong>: Actually, Frodo was the one who was responsible for saving the other hobbits from the wights - if it hadn't been for his stamina, he never would have called for Tom Bombadil. As for him not being able to manage it on his own - he was barel clvl5 at the time, in ToME terms. :P No character can take on the Wight-king of the Barrow-downs at that character level. <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile4.png" alt=";)" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
 <strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Frodo made it to Mt Doom beyond all expectations, even if he did have a bit of help. The others at the Council of Elrond were far more intent upon arguing with one another. Frodo was the one who stood up and took responsibility for the destruction of the One. 
</p>

        <ul>

  <strong><a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a></strong>: Powerdiving in Wizard-mode and removing the one from the source files is <em>hardly</em> laudable behaviour. Next you're going to say that Bilbo's CharDump (AKA "There and Back Again" or "The Hobbit") wasn't edited! I'm appalled that we're condoning this... <p>
  <strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: So basically, you're dissing the entire Lord of the Rings series. 
</p>

