   <a href="./SimonSorc">SimonSorc</a>: When I said barrows-down, I meant the dungeon not the quest! I took the name in the in-game spoilers; I systematically skip it. Does it have another name? <p>
   And oh yeah. Due to popular demand, I will no longer diss Frodo. And I will actually read Tolkien, not just web pages about it and the forums who tend to humor him; and Kavlax the many-headed has one brain for how many heads again (just to be on topic)?? 
</p>

                <ul>

    <strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: <em><strong>WHAT?!!?!</strong></em> You haven't <em>read</em> Tolkien?!? Shame, shame, shame on you, that a) you are missing out on a fantastic experience, b) that you are passing judgement on things when you don't know what you are talking about. I thought you were hyperlexic. Go read Tolkien. Immediately. You'll love it. <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile.png" alt=":)" height="15" width="15"> 
                </ul>


   Oops, looks like Maylith is responding to <a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a> and not me. 
                <ul>

    <strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Yes, I was responding to Ravenred. 
                </ul>


   Oh, well, I won't take back my apology for Frodo. And like Gandalf said, Hobbits are amazing creatures! He just needs a few stat potion that's all - quite normal for clev5. <p>
   (how did you come to the clev 5 idea? Why not 10 or 1?) 
</p>

                <ul>

    <strong><a href="./FuriousOne">FuriousOne</a></strong>: Well, when they were at the Barrow-downs in the book, the hobbits hadn't done much but flee in terror, hadn't killed anyone, and didn't even have any weapons! But they did make it through the Old Forest (hmm, now I will have to make a point of having a char go through the Old Forest without killing anything). At level 10, any char can reasonably kill a worthy foe, but at level 5 not yet. <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/biggrin.png" alt=":D" height="15" width="15"> 
                </ul>            </ul>        </ul>    </ul>


<p>
Kavlax the many-headed but one-brained: Can we get back on topic please? I need my other heads to be counted (insert cheesy educative game music)! Can you help? 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Back to Kavlax. I agree with <a href="./StarweaverBlue">StarweaverBlue</a>. If a one-brained creature possesses a manyheaded one.... I think your "wiring" isn't suited to control all the different heads independently. At best, all the heads would be trying to do the same thing. Magic or no, the sensory input of lots of heads trying to do their own thing simultaneously would probably cause a major sanity hit for a possessor who was originally single-headed. Hey... there's an idea!  
</p>
<p>
For possession of multiple-headed critters, you could either: 
</p>

    <ol type="1">

    <li>
<p>
Control one head very well (i.e. the current situation) 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
Control all heads for more damage/etc, but take a sanity hit for each round you do so. 
</p>
</li>

    </ol>


<p>
<strong><a href="./BurbLulls">BurbLulls</a></strong>: Why should all the heads need full poesession if all you're doing is putting helmets/amulets on them? Their physical benefits should still be present! 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./SimonSorc">SimonSorc</a>: why not stick with the status quo rules and make Kavlax many headed for purpose of equipment slots just like Krakens already are? For Valar's sake, it's the FUN option and it's already in the game!! And Kavlax being not too powerful anyhow, this isn't unbalancing. 
</p>
